First, lets summarize our data.

For this, I thought it might be interesting to look at age (juvenile/adult) and distance traveled for each bat from the last known location.

p1<- ggplot(bats, aes(x=day.tracking, y=miles, group=ID, color=ID, shape=ID)) + 
  geom_point(size=4, position = position_dodge2(width=.33, preserve = "total")) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::dollar_format()) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  labs(title="Aerobatics: How Far Do Bats Travel", x= "Day Tracking", y = "Miles traveled")

  p1
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

summary <- bats %>%
  group_by(age, day.tracking) %>%
  summarise(n = n(),
           mean_move=mean(miles),
           se_move=sd(miles)/sqrt(n()))

#relevel factors into intuitive order
data_emm$day.tracking <- factor(data_emm$day.tracking, levels = c("first", "second", "third", "fourth"))

p<- ggplot(data_emm, aes(x=day.tracking, y=emmean, group=age, color=age)) +

For this example, a study looked at three different herds of bison and recorded their weights at two different times. Each herd was located in a different region of a grassland and researchers wanted to test how drought and changing temperatures may cause fluctuations in weights.

Lets begin.....

bison <- read.csv("bison.csv")

data(bison)
